and your institution. Phones on silent for the session.

27
00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:29.600
And, yeah, I don't think there's anything else from me.

28
00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:33.280
So our first speaker is going to be Salman Punekar from NYU,

29
00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:37.700
and Salman is going to talk about some very exciting work using new

30
00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:42.340
IL-2 agonist STK-12 to

31
00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:45.740
combine with pembrolizumab and chemotherapy in non-small cell lung cancer.

32
00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:47.920
So, Salman, over to you.

33
00:01:52.300 --> 00:01:54.040
Thank you. Thank you very much. Good afternoon, everybody.

34
00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:58.100
Thank you for the opportunity. Let me just get things situated.

35
00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:02.460
All right. Very good. Thank you for the opportunity to present new data on

36
00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:05.780
STK-12 in combination with pembrolizumab and

37
00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:09.480
chemotherapy as first-line treatment for PD-L1 negative

38
00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:11.840
non-squamous, non-small cell lung cancer.

39
00:02:12.740 --> 00:02:14.340
Here are my disclosures.

40
00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:20.740
PD-L1 negative tumors account for roughly 40% of newly

41
00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:24.600
diagnosed non-squamous, non-small cell lung cancer and

42
00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:26.700
represent a very significant unmet need.

43
00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:29.840
These tumors respond poorly to chemo IO,

44
00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:33.950
and they are frequently enriched for alterations in STK11,

45
00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:38.320
KEAP1, and SMARCA4, a biology that is characterized

46
00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:41.880
by immune cold microenvironments, low T cell

47
00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:45.840
infiltration, poor antigen presentation, and intrinsic

48
00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:47.650
resistance to checkpoint inhibition.

49
00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:52.780
STK-12 is a recombinant IL-2 engineered to selectively

50
00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:56.390
expand antigen-experienced anti-tumor T cells

51
00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:00.609
while sparing NK cells, naive T cells, and

52
00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:04.460
regulatory T cells, which are the primary drivers of classic

53
00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:06.640
IL-2 toxicity and resistance.

54
00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:09.920
The rationale for this combination is straightforward.

55
00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:14.700
By adding STK-12 to chemotherapy and checkpoint inhibition, we

56
00:03:14.780 --> 00:03:18.660
aim to restore T cell effector function and improve

57
00:03:18.820 --> 00:03:22.380
T cell trafficking within the tumor microenvironment without the

58
00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:25.940
toxicity that has historically limited IL-2-based approaches.

59
00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:31.980
In this Phase I study, we evaluated STK-12 in

60
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.280
combination with pembrolizumab and carboplatin.

61
00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:38.720
STK-12 was administered subcutaneously every three weeks in the

62
00:03:38.780 --> 00:03:39.640
outpatient setting

63
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.680
to patients with Stage 4 non-squamous, non-small cell lung

64
00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:45.810
cancer in the front line.

65
00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:50.100
Importantly, this was a high-risk population by design.

66
00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:53.140
Eighty-nine percent of patients were PD-L1 negative.

67
00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:57.500
The core was enriched for STK11, KEAP1, and SMARCA4

68
00:03:57.580 --> 00:03:58.380
alterations.

69
00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:03.300
Forty-two percent were TTF-1 negative, 22% had

70
00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:06.820
mucinous histology, and 25% were never smokers.

71
00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:11.520
Notably, 22% harbored STK11 and

72
00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:15.250
KEAP1 co-mutations, a notoriously difficult to treat

73
00:04:15.420 --> 00:04:16.921
treatment-resistant subgroup.

74
00:04:17.840 --> 00:04:21.579
Each of these features are independently associated with poor outcomes on chemo

75
00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:25.590
IO. So collectively, this represents a particularly

76
00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:27.200
challenging patient population.

77
00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:33.100
Turning to safety, among 39 evaluable patients,

78
00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:36.140
STK-12 plus chemo IO demonstrated a

79
00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:39.660
manageable safety profile. There were no treatment

80
00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:43.560
discontinuations due to TRAEs, no DLTs, and no

81
00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:44.540
Grade 5 events.

82
00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:48.580
Consistent with the mechanism of STK-12, the most common

83
00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:52.480
toxicity was maculopapular rash, occurring in about half

84
00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:56.260
of patients. It was rapidly reversible with short

85
00:04:56.300 --> 00:04:59.020
courses of steroids or IL-4 pathway inhibitors.

86
00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:01.220
All Grade 4 events,

87
00:05:01.580 --> 00:05:05.280
neutropenia, thrombocytopenia,

88
00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:08.880
febrile neutropenia, and leukopenia, were classic of chemotherapy.

89
00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:13.920
Critically, we observed minimal classic IL-2 toxicity.

90
00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:17.840
There was no significant transaminitis or vascular leak syndrome.

91
00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:21.680
Overall, the safety profile was consistent with what we would expect from

92
00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:23.020
chemo IO alone.

93
00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:30.240
In the overall population, we observed an overall response rate

94
00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:33.900
of 50% and a disease control rate of 97%.

95
00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:38.400
To put this into context, historical benchmarks for PD-L1 negative

96
00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:42.750
non-squamous, non-small cell lung cancer treated with pembro or

97
00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:46.700
cemiplimab-based combinations report response rates in the range

98
00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:48.500
of 23% to 32%.

99
00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:53.460
PFS and OS data are still maturing, but the efficacy signal thus far

100
00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:57.430
is very encouraging, particularly given the high-risk profile of this

101
00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:01.414
patient population.The

102
00:06:01.484 --> 00:06:05.384
selectivity of STK-12 is reflected in its PK and PD

103
00:06:05.464 --> 00:06:05.884
profile.

104
00:06:06.824 --> 00:06:10.624
STK-12 has a half-life of nearly six days, substantially

105
00:06:10.704 --> 00:06:13.944
longer than traditional IL-2, enabling convenient

106
00:06:14.524 --> 00:06:15.724
every three-week dosing.

107
00:06:16.844 --> 00:06:20.584
Pharmacodynamically, we observed robust and sustained induction of

108
00:06:20.644 --> 00:06:22.224
interferon gamma and IP-10,

109
00:06:23.064 --> 00:06:26.583
both of which drive CDA positive and Type I immune responses.

110
00:06:27.824 --> 00:06:31.404
IP-10 is an interferon gamma-inducible chemokine that plays a key

111
00:06:31.544 --> 00:06:35.164
role in recruiting T cells into the tumor microenvironment.

112
00:06:36.054 --> 00:06:39.984
This activation was sustained across treatment cycles, consistent

113
00:06:40.024 --> 00:06:43.514
with the long half-life and ongoing pharmacodynamic

114
00:06:43.584 --> 00:06:45.104
engagement of STK-12.

115
00:06:46.664 --> 00:06:49.224
Equally important is what we did not see.

116
00:06:49.264 --> 00:06:52.424
There was minimal induction of IL-6 and TN alpha alpha,

117
00:06:53.064 --> 00:06:56.904
consistent with the absence of vascular leak and cytokine release toxicities.

118
00:06:57.784 --> 00:07:00.844
This is precisely what we want from a precision IL-2 approach.

119
00:07:01.494 --> 00:07:05.444
Potent immune activation where it matters without systemic inflammatory

120
00:07:05.484 --> 00:07:05.994
toxicity.

121
00:07:08.684 --> 00:07:11.684
At the cellular level, the data reinforced this selectivity.

122
00:07:12.484 --> 00:07:16.244
We did not observe significant expansion of NK cells or regulatory T

123
00:07:16.324 --> 00:07:19.444
cells, and overall lymphocyte counts remained stable.

124
00:07:20.324 --> 00:07:23.984
What we did see, however, was strong expansion of 4-1BB

125
00:07:24.024 --> 00:07:27.424
positive CD8 T cells, a marker of recent antigen

126
00:07:27.504 --> 00:07:28.034
activation,

127
00:07:28.904 --> 00:07:32.164
supporting the hypothesis that STK-12 is selectively

128
00:07:32.204 --> 00:07:34.414
engaging antigen-experienced T cells.

129
00:07:35.484 --> 00:07:38.974
We also observed clear evidence of T cell reinvigoration,

130
00:07:39.664 --> 00:07:43.284
demonstrated by robust proliferation of PD-1 positive

131
00:07:43.364 --> 00:07:44.364
CD8 T cells.

132
00:07:45.384 --> 00:07:49.064
Importantly, the majority of these cells were CD28 positive,

133
00:07:49.684 --> 00:07:53.544
indicating a co-stimulation competent memory-capable

134
00:07:53.604 --> 00:07:57.204
phenotype, not just proliferation of terminally exhausted

135
00:07:57.524 --> 00:08:01.204
cells. So this is not broad, indiscriminate immune

136
00:08:01.304 --> 00:08:04.624
activation. This is targeted engagement of the effector

137
00:08:04.704 --> 00:08:05.364
component

138
00:08:06.324 --> 00:08:08.904
of cells most relevant to anti-tumor immunity.

139
00:08:11.504 --> 00:08:15.424
At the clonal level, T cell receptor sequencing provides further support

140
00:08:15.464 --> 00:08:18.924
for the selective, yet robust immune response.

141
00:08:19.004 --> 00:08:22.984
We observed clonal expansion, including greater than tenfold expansion

142
00:08:23.024 --> 00:08:24.254
of preexisting clones,

143
00:08:25.184 --> 00:08:28.584
and importantly, the emergence of numerously previously

144
00:08:28.624 --> 00:08:30.324
undetected T cell clonotypes.

145
00:08:31.284 --> 00:08:34.965
After just one cycle of treatment, 3.5% of circulating T

146
00:08:35.004 --> 00:08:37.595
cells were derived from newly expanded clones,

147
00:08:38.544 --> 00:08:41.684
suggesting antigen-driven remodeling of the T cell repertoire.

148
00:08:42.834 --> 00:08:46.604
Critically, the degree of clonal expansion seemed to correlate with clinical

149
00:08:46.664 --> 00:08:49.824
response, directly linking these transitional

150
00:08:49.844 --> 00:08:51.354
findings to efficacy.

151
00:08:53.924 --> 00:08:57.904
I'd now like to focus on two subpopulations defined by alterations

152
00:08:57.924 --> 00:08:59.064
in tumor suppressor genes.

153
00:08:59.864 --> 00:09:03.424
Half of efficacy evaluable patients harbored at least one alteration in

154
00:09:03.504 --> 00:09:06.454
STK11, KEAP1, or SMARCA4.

155
00:09:07.344 --> 00:09:10.884
These three genes are located in close proximity on the short arm of

156
00:09:10.904 --> 00:09:14.444
chromosome 19, are frequently co-altered, and are

157
00:09:14.484 --> 00:09:18.164
associated with metabolic reprogramming and impaired immune function.

158
00:09:19.364 --> 00:09:22.984
In this subgroup, we observed an objective response rate of

159
00:09:23.264 --> 00:09:27.094
61% and a disease control rate of 100%.

160
00:09:27.704 --> 00:09:30.993
This is particularly noteworthy because these tumors are

161
00:09:31.024 --> 00:09:32.844
characteristically non-inflamed,

162
00:09:33.724 --> 00:09:37.184
with reduced T cell infiltration and impaired antigen presentation.

163
00:09:38.184 --> 00:09:41.884
Published data report response rates in the single digits to low

164
00:09:42.024 --> 00:09:45.824
30% range, with median progression-free survival of three to five

165
00:09:45.864 --> 00:09:46.164
months.

166
00:09:47.084 --> 00:09:50.534
And importantly, the activity we observed here was in a subgroup that was

167
00:09:50.604 --> 00:09:53.984
overwhelmingly PD-L1 negative. Fourteen of 18

168
00:09:54.424 --> 00:09:58.204
patients were PD-L1 negative, and the remaining four had PD-L1

169
00:09:58.244 --> 00:09:59.604
expression of just 1%.

170
00:10:02.024 --> 00:10:04.844
Drilling down further, we enrolled eight patients with

171
00:10:04.904 --> 00:10:08.864
STK11/KEAP1 co-mutated non-small cell lung cancer, six

172
00:10:08.924 --> 00:10:10.364
of whom were PD-L1 negative.

173
00:10:11.204 --> 00:10:14.524
This population represents approximately 10% of

174
00:10:14.604 --> 00:10:18.324
non-squamous, non-small cell lung cancer and constitutes one of the

175
00:10:18.364 --> 00:10:20.313
highest unmet needs in the frontline setting.

176
00:10:21.243 --> 00:10:24.383
Historically, response rates are in the single digits to low teens.

177
00:10:25.304 --> 00:10:28.784
Forty percent of patients progress on the first scan, and median

178
00:10:28.804 --> 00:10:31.544
progression-free survival is approximately only three months.

179
00:10:32.584 --> 00:10:36.124
With STK-12 plus chemo IO, we observed a response rate of

180
00:10:36.304 --> 00:10:39.994
50%, and no patient experienced progressive disease on their first

181
00:10:40.024 --> 00:10:43.804
scan. In this co-mutated subgroup,

182
00:10:44.084 --> 00:10:47.864
the median progression-free survival was 5.5 months, with two

183
00:10:47.904 --> 00:10:49.024
patients still on treatment.

184
00:10:49.834 --> 00:10:53.564
The six-month overall survival rate was 88%, with median

185
00:10:53.684 --> 00:10:57.544
overall survival not yet reached at a median follow-up of 6.8 months.

186
00:10:58.544 --> 00:11:02.304
We acknowledge the sample size is small, but these

187
00:11:02.324 --> 00:11:06.224
results appear meaningfully different from historical benchmarks.

188
00:11:07.044 --> 00:11:10.954
To our knowledge, the only available Phase III data in this population comes

189
00:11:10.984 --> 00:11:14.864
from the subgroup analysis of IMpower-150, which reported

190
00:11:14.874 --> 00:11:18.644
a median PFS of three months and a median OS of 5.4

191
00:11:18.684 --> 00:11:21.784
months across pooled treatment arms.

192
00:11:22.284 --> 00:11:26.184
When we examine the translational biology in the STK11/KEAP1 co-mutated

193
00:11:26.264 --> 00:11:28.984
population, the story becomes even more compelling.

194
00:11:29.644 --> 00:11:32.944
At baseline, these tumors showed reduced proliferation of

195
00:11:33.004 --> 00:11:36.384
antigen-activated CD8 T cells, consistent with their

196
00:11:36.444 --> 00:11:37.704
immunosuppressed phenotype.

197
00:11:38.584 --> 00:11:42.564
After treatment with STK-12, proliferation of 4-1BB positive

198
00:11:42.744 --> 00:11:44.984
antigen-activated cells was restored.

199
00:11:45.844 --> 00:11:49.764
We observed a marked increase in proliferating PD-1 positive CD8 T

200
00:11:49.804 --> 00:11:52.924
cells and robust clonal T cell expansion.

201
00:11:53.644 --> 00:11:57.384
So even in this highly immunosuppressed setting, STK-12

202
00:11:57.444 --> 00:12:00.604
appears to reengage the immune system and restore functional T cell

203
00:12:00.644 --> 00:12:04.368
responses.Given that these tumors often carry high tumor

204
00:12:04.448 --> 00:12:07.848
mutational burden yet remain unresponsive to checkpoint

205
00:12:07.888 --> 00:12:11.688
inhibition these data suggest that STK-12 may be

206
00:12:11.728 --> 00:12:14.248
capable of reversing underlying immunosuppression

207
00:12:15.728 --> 00:12:19.688
in summary STK-12 demonstrates consistent and selective

208
00:12:19.748 --> 00:12:23.698
immune activation robust T-cell engagement and encouraging clinical

209
00:12:23.768 --> 00:12:26.488
activity across multiple treatment-resistant subgroups

210
00:12:27.628 --> 00:12:31.448
STK-12 has the potential to convert immunologically cold

211
00:12:31.488 --> 00:12:35.388
into responsive ones addressing a major unmet need in first-line

212
00:12:35.468 --> 00:12:36.518
non-small cell lung cancer

213
00:12:37.388 --> 00:12:41.198
with a manageable safety profile and strong biologic rationale these

214
00:12:41.208 --> 00:12:44.668
data support continued development a randomized phase two study

215
00:12:44.828 --> 00:12:46.288
synergy is currently enrolling

216
00:12:47.768 --> 00:12:51.548
thank you very much we'd like to thank everybody who contributed to this study

217
00:12:51.888 --> 00:12:53.528
from the patients to all of the staff

218
00:13:00.708 --> 00:13:03.948
Thank you, Selman. For questions, please come up to the mic.

219
00:13:07.247 --> 00:13:08.928
Selman, maybe I can start with a question.

220
00:13:09.348 --> 00:13:10.488
So I think

221
00:13:11.688 --> 00:13:12.308
one of the most

222
00:13:14.028 --> 00:13:17.928
common things that people have noticed in prior IL-2 cytokine-based therapies

223
00:13:18.048 --> 00:13:21.428
is systemic toxicities, and this is a partial agonist.

224
00:13:22.548 --> 00:13:26.368
Is it the receptor biasing for what it binds that is responsible

225
00:13:26.428 --> 00:13:29.328
for the separation of efficacy and toxicity here?

226
00:13:30.328 --> 00:13:32.318
Yeah, I'll just point you towards the

227
00:13:34.108 --> 00:13:37.768
right here. So in the bottom right-hand side, you can

228
00:13:37.888 --> 00:13:39.248
see how it

229
00:13:40.308 --> 00:13:44.208
is biased towards activating antigen-activated T cells, but not necessarily the NK

230
00:13:44.248 --> 00:13:47.928
cells and the CD28 cells. So most of the toxicity that we see

231
00:13:48.468 --> 00:13:51.748
is with cytokine release and vascular leak.

232
00:13:52.628 --> 00:13:56.508
And then the induction of Tregs results in a lot of the

233
00:13:56.548 --> 00:13:58.378
resistance to IL-2-based approaches.

234
00:13:58.928 --> 00:14:01.198
And so you lose that therapeutic window when you use traditional

235
00:14:01.268 --> 00:14:03.348
IL-2.

236
00:14:03.358 --> 00:14:05.948
Okay. I also have a question follow-up to that.

237
00:14:06.048 --> 00:14:10.028
So you showed really nicely that there's no expansion of NK cells and Tregs in the

238
00:14:10.968 --> 00:14:12.897
peripheral blood. What about in the tissue?

239
00:14:12.908 --> 00:14:16.788
Did you see any increase in NK cell population following your

240
00:14:16.848 --> 00:14:19.028
treatment or any increase in Tregs?

241
00:14:19.388 --> 00:14:23.228
So that's a very interesting question, something that we'd like to study.

242
00:14:23.238 --> 00:14:26.428
We don't have on-treatment and progression biopsies, unfortunately, in this patient

243
00:14:26.448 --> 00:14:29.268
population, so we're limited to the periphery.

244
00:14:29.288 --> 00:14:32.528
But that's definitely something that we'd like to demonstrate in future work.

245
00:14:34.488 --> 00:14:37.108
Selman, I have one more since nobody is at the mic right now.

246
00:14:37.268 --> 00:14:39.648
I feel like maybe I can just take all my questions.

247
00:14:40.748 --> 00:14:41.028
Please.

248
00:14:42.308 --> 00:14:45.288
This is an engineered cytokine variant.

249
00:14:45.408 --> 00:14:49.108
How different is it from IL-2 in amino acid

250
00:14:49.148 --> 00:14:52.948
conservation space? And is there an immune reaction against the

251
00:14:52.968 --> 00:14:56.268
cytokine? Have you looked for anti-drug antibodies against it?

252
00:14:57.988 --> 00:15:01.738
I can't answer the question as to how similar of an amino

253
00:15:01.768 --> 00:15:04.068
acid sequence it is. I don't know the answer to that.

254
00:15:06.888 --> 00:15:07.668
I actually-

255
00:15:08.988 --> 00:15:09.828
Three amino acids.

256
00:15:09.848 --> 00:15:10.448
Three amino acids. There we go, so-

257
00:15:10.508 --> 00:15:11.698
Only three amino acid changes.

258
00:15:11.698 --> 00:15:11.928
Yeah.

259
00:15:15.348 --> 00:15:19.128
And presumably you have looked for anti-drug antibodies, or

260
00:15:19.548 --> 00:15:21.548
no? Because obviously in engineered cytokines,

261
00:15:22.568 --> 00:15:24.608
neutralization is a problem that people would consider.

262
00:15:31.368 --> 00:15:35.168
Most IL-2s, even aldus looking, see some antibodies

263
00:15:35.248 --> 00:15:37.248
typically after continued dosing.

264
00:15:37.308 --> 00:15:41.188
So we see after cycle six, eight, and so on, we see

265
00:15:41.308 --> 00:15:45.148
antibodies, but concentrations and biomarkers are still very active,

266
00:15:45.248 --> 00:15:46.728
so they're probably not neutralizing.

267
00:15:49.148 --> 00:15:50.188
Very interesting. Thank you, guys.

268
00:15:51.348 --> 00:15:52.288
Okay. Thank you very much.

269
00:15:54.808 --> 00:15:58.608
Okay, so now we move on to our second talk, which

270
00:15:58.688 --> 00:16:01.668
is going to be delivered by Dr. Meilin Li from Houston

271
00:16:01.748 --> 00:16:05.608
Methodist. It's going to be focused on tertiary

272
00:16:05.708 --> 00:16:09.308
lymphoid structures and how they define response to durvalumab,

273
00:16:09.368 --> 00:16:13.228
trastuzumab, and pertuzumab combination in HER2-enriched early breast cancer.

274
00:16:20.488 --> 00:16:20.668
Hi.

275
00:16:21.907 --> 00:16:25.828
Good afternoon. Thank you to the ACR organizers for this opportunity to

276
00:16:25.868 --> 00:16:29.708
share our work. My name is Meilin, and I'm a sixth-year MD, PhD

277
00:16:29.768 --> 00:16:33.488
student in Dr. Jenny Chang's lab at Houston Methodist Research

278
00:16:33.528 --> 00:16:37.268
Institute. And today, I'll be presenting our study on tertiary lymphoid

279
00:16:37.388 --> 00:16:41.088
structure-associated immune circuits and how they define response to

280
00:16:41.108 --> 00:16:44.828
durvalumab, trastuzumab, and pertuzumab in HER2-enriched

281
00:16:44.928 --> 00:16:45.908
early breast cancer.

282
00:16:47.808 --> 00:16:50.008
I have no financial relationships to disclose.

283
00:16:51.648 --> 00:16:55.148
So to orient us, I'll start with the clinical challenge of de-escalation

284
00:16:55.228 --> 00:16:59.088
strategies for HER2-positive breast cancer, introduce our DTP

285
00:16:59.188 --> 00:17:03.008
clinical trial and PCR outcomes, share some interesting cell

286
00:17:03.048 --> 00:17:06.469
types that we identified on our single-nucleus RNA sequencing

287
00:17:06.488 --> 00:17:10.008
data and how these cell types relate to one another in our Xenium

288
00:17:10.028 --> 00:17:13.588
data, then conclude with some interesting findings.

289
00:17:15.628 --> 00:17:19.398
So HER2 positive breast cancer is increasingly defined by biologically

290
00:17:19.508 --> 00:17:23.328
guided treatment. Historically, HER2 positive breast cancer,

291
00:17:23.388 --> 00:17:27.238
like triple-negative breast cancer, was considered an aggressive disease with

292
00:17:27.268 --> 00:17:30.968
poor prognosis. This changed in the 1980s with the

293
00:17:31.028 --> 00:17:34.748
identification of the oncogenic function of HER2 and

294
00:17:34.808 --> 00:17:38.598
the eventual development of anti-HER2 targeted therapies,

295
00:17:38.728 --> 00:17:42.048
including monoclonal antibodies, tyrosine kinase

296
00:17:42.088 --> 00:17:45.848
inhibitors, and more recently, antibody drug conjugates.

297
00:17:47.288 --> 00:17:51.168
In parallel, intrinsic subtyping has refined our understanding of breast

298
00:17:51.208 --> 00:17:52.098
tumor biology.

299
00:17:52.988 --> 00:17:56.818
HER2 positive disease is clinically defined by HER2 protein

300
00:17:56.868 --> 00:18:00.048
expression seen on immunohistochemistry or gene

301
00:18:00.108 --> 00:18:02.508
amplification on fluorescence in C2

302
00:18:02.548 --> 00:18:06.356
hybridizationHowever, the HER2-enriched molecular

303
00:18:06.476 --> 00:18:10.076
subtype is defined by gene expression, often by bulk RNA

304
00:18:10.116 --> 00:18:13.646
sequencing. So while these categories overlap, they're not

305
00:18:13.716 --> 00:18:14.256
equivalent.

306
00:18:15.606 --> 00:18:18.876
Despite this, the progress in preclinical and

307
00:18:18.916 --> 00:18:20.346
translational research,

308
00:18:21.676 --> 00:18:25.116
chemotherapy remains the backbone of treatment with toxicities such as

309
00:18:25.196 --> 00:18:28.906
long-term neuropathic pain and cardiac dysfunction accepted as

310
00:18:28.936 --> 00:18:31.416
unfortunate but unavoidable side effects.

311
00:18:32.316 --> 00:18:36.216
So when immune checkpoint inhibitors showed great success in triple-negative

312
00:18:36.236 --> 00:18:39.466
breast cancer, we and others became interested in whether

313
00:18:39.476 --> 00:18:42.826
immunotherapy could be adapted for HER2 positive breast cancer.

314
00:18:43.976 --> 00:18:47.456
And this led us to ask, if HER2-enriched tumors are

315
00:18:47.476 --> 00:18:51.116
especially dependent on HER2 signaling, could we omit

316
00:18:51.196 --> 00:18:54.616
chemotherapy for this subset of patients and treat them with

317
00:18:54.676 --> 00:18:58.576
immunotherapy and anti-HER2 targeted treatments

318
00:18:58.716 --> 00:18:59.096
alone?

319
00:19:00.836 --> 00:19:04.036
And this led to our clinical trial using durvalumab, an

320
00:19:04.046 --> 00:19:07.896
anti-PD-L1 immune checkpoint inhibitor with trastuzumab

321
00:19:07.906 --> 00:19:11.066
and pertuzumab, two anti-HER2 targeting antibodies,

322
00:19:11.516 --> 00:19:14.976
collectively called DTP, as a chemotherapy-free regimen.

323
00:19:16.376 --> 00:19:19.796
For DTP, we screened 51 HER2 positive hormone

324
00:19:19.836 --> 00:19:23.516
receptor-negative patients, 45 of whom were HER2 enriched.

325
00:19:24.396 --> 00:19:28.376
Thirty-nine patients began the clinical trial with us, and 37 of them

326
00:19:28.456 --> 00:19:31.476
completed the trial and were included in the final analysis.

327
00:19:32.936 --> 00:19:36.656
All patients underwent baseline clinical exam and imaging with either

328
00:19:36.716 --> 00:19:40.656
ultrasound or mammogram. And after six cycles of DTP,

329
00:19:40.876 --> 00:19:44.756
we repeated the clinical exam and imaging, now with MRI, to assess

330
00:19:44.856 --> 00:19:45.756
tumor response.

331
00:19:47.036 --> 00:19:50.916
Patients with adequate tumor reduction proceeded to surgery and pathologic

332
00:19:50.996 --> 00:19:51.796
evaluation.

333
00:19:52.656 --> 00:19:56.296
Patients without adequate tumor reduction

334
00:19:56.396 --> 00:19:59.666
received standard of care salvage chemotherapy with

335
00:19:59.676 --> 00:20:03.136
docetaxel carboplatin, trastuzumab, pertuzumab,

336
00:20:03.376 --> 00:20:06.636
abbreviated here as TCHP, and then went to surgery.

337
00:20:08.076 --> 00:20:11.836
One of our readouts was pathologic complete response, or PCR,

338
00:20:11.856 --> 00:20:15.716
defined as residual cancer burden, RCB, of zero, meaning

339
00:20:15.776 --> 00:20:18.796
no invasive tumor was seen on the surgical specimen.

340
00:20:19.896 --> 00:20:23.496
DTP alone achieved a PCR rate of 49%, which

341
00:20:23.536 --> 00:20:26.996
increased to an overall of 54% when including the

342
00:20:27.036 --> 00:20:29.356
patients who were salvaged with TCHP.

343
00:20:31.096 --> 00:20:34.496
We sequenced treatment-naive needle biopsies from all 37

344
00:20:34.576 --> 00:20:38.226
patients but focused our analysis on the 31 patients treated with

345
00:20:38.256 --> 00:20:39.126
DTP alone.

346
00:20:40.236 --> 00:20:44.216
And using single-nucleus RNA sequencing, Xenium 5K spatial

347
00:20:44.256 --> 00:20:48.236
transcriptomics, and multiplex IHC, we wanted to figure out

348
00:20:48.456 --> 00:20:52.176
what cell types were present in our samples, how did they correlate with

349
00:20:52.236 --> 00:20:55.376
clinical response, and how are they spatially organized.

350
00:20:57.416 --> 00:21:01.136
And in our cleaned-up single-nucleus data set, we analyzed around

351
00:21:01.416 --> 00:21:05.296
500,000 total cells, including 170,000 immune cells,

352
00:21:05.716 --> 00:21:09.256
which clusters here in this UMAP broadly into B, myeloid,

353
00:21:09.416 --> 00:21:11.756
NK, plasma, and T cell populations.

354
00:21:12.876 --> 00:21:16.636
We then reclustered each lineage at higher resolution and annotated a

355
00:21:16.676 --> 00:21:19.476
total of 23 T and NK cell clusters,

356
00:21:20.516 --> 00:21:22.736
18 myeloid dendritic cell clusters,

357
00:21:23.616 --> 00:21:27.336
and 13 B and plasma cell clusters. And this led us to

358
00:21:27.346 --> 00:21:31.026
ask, okay, now that we've done all this work, which of these cell types are

359
00:21:31.076 --> 00:21:32.446
associated with response?

360
00:21:33.376 --> 00:21:37.106
And while there were many, we focused on these three, these T follicular

361
00:21:37.196 --> 00:21:41.036
helper like CD4 positive T cells, LAMB3 positive

362
00:21:41.116 --> 00:21:44.835
mature dendritic cells, and cycling B cells.

363
00:21:44.876 --> 00:21:48.436
These subtypes were significantly enriched in treatment-naive

364
00:21:48.556 --> 00:21:51.856
tumors from patients who eventually achieved PCR, shown here in

365
00:21:51.876 --> 00:21:55.636
blue, and depleted in patients who later had substantial

366
00:21:55.656 --> 00:21:57.656
residual disease, shown here in red.

367
00:21:59.816 --> 00:22:03.756
But are these significant cell types acting independently, or are they organized

368
00:22:03.796 --> 00:22:05.596
as part of a broader immune program?

369
00:22:06.365 --> 00:22:10.136
And to answer this question, we used hierarchical clustering of cell type

370
00:22:10.196 --> 00:22:14.066
abundance and co-occurrence across tumors to identify five

371
00:22:14.096 --> 00:22:17.616
immune modules, shown here by the colored labels along this heat map.

372
00:22:18.436 --> 00:22:22.195
In one of these modules, module two on the lower right, contained the

373
00:22:22.256 --> 00:22:26.055
same T follicular helper, B, and mature dendritic

374
00:22:26.065 --> 00:22:28.176
cells we found in our previous analysis.

375
00:22:28.896 --> 00:22:32.766
And overall, this module as a whole also strongly correlated with

376
00:22:32.796 --> 00:22:33.356
PCR.

377
00:22:34.776 --> 00:22:38.376
Because these cell types were enriched individually and within the same immune

378
00:22:38.436 --> 00:22:42.376
module, we thought they might reflect tertiary lymphoid structure, or

379
00:22:42.496 --> 00:22:43.796
TLS organization.

380
00:22:44.996 --> 00:22:48.096
TLS are organized immune aggregates that form in

381
00:22:48.136 --> 00:22:52.096
non-lymphoid tissues, including tumors, and support local

382
00:22:52.156 --> 00:22:53.796
adaptive immune responses.

383
00:22:54.756 --> 00:22:57.716
They exist along a maturation spectrum from these loose

384
00:22:57.896 --> 00:23:01.656
aggregates into organized structures with B and T cell

385
00:23:01.796 --> 00:23:05.376
specific zones. And mature TLSs can also develop

386
00:23:05.386 --> 00:23:09.136
germinal center features and function like local mini lymph nodes to

387
00:23:09.176 --> 00:23:10.826
support antitumor immunity.

388
00:23:12.156 --> 00:23:16.066
But sequencing only tells us which cell types are present, not where they are.

389
00:23:16.556 --> 00:23:20.316
So to test whether this module reflects TLS organization, we

390
00:23:20.356 --> 00:23:22.146
move on to spatial transcriptomics.

391
00:23:24.436 --> 00:23:28.046
We ran Xenium on a subset of patient samples and transferred over our

392
00:23:28.076 --> 00:23:30.955
single-nucleus cell type labels.

393
00:23:31.076 --> 00:23:34.816
Here we can orient ourselves with the H&amp;E image on the left and the

394
00:23:34.876 --> 00:23:38.616
corresponding Xenium image on the right, with nuclear staining in blue,

395
00:23:39.256 --> 00:23:43.156
cell boundary markers in magenta, interior protein in green,

396
00:23:43.536 --> 00:23:44.736
and RNA in yellow.

397
00:23:45.986 --> 00:23:49.906
We can also zoom in on one particular region or structure shown on the lower

398
00:23:50.016 --> 00:23:53.996
left, and then see which cell types from our single-nucleus annotations are

399
00:23:54.005 --> 00:23:55.516
present, shown on the right.

400
00:23:56.616 --> 00:23:59.856
We can also see the same region, now one cell type at a time,

401
00:24:00.316 --> 00:24:02.816
including our previously defined response-associated

402
00:24:02.916 --> 00:24:06.748
populations.The T follicular helper cells

403
00:24:06.808 --> 00:24:10.778
here in purple are mature dendritic cells here in yellow and

404
00:24:10.828 --> 00:24:14.268
then a spectrum of B-cell populations on the top in red.

405
00:24:14.948 --> 00:24:18.548
We also find some other canonically associated TLS subtypes, including

406
00:24:18.628 --> 00:24:21.888
interspersed CD4 and CD8 T cells,

407
00:24:22.368 --> 00:24:25.568
plasma cells, and supporting stroma cells, including reticular

408
00:24:25.668 --> 00:24:28.147
fibroblasts and lymphatic endothelial cells.

409
00:24:30.308 --> 00:24:34.248
Next, we ask how to quantify these response-associated interactions

410
00:24:34.268 --> 00:24:35.188
in our spatial data.

411
00:24:36.168 --> 00:24:39.808
For this, we defined a niche as a spatial co-occurrence of a

412
00:24:39.868 --> 00:24:43.288
CD4 positive T cell, a B cell, and a dendritic cell

413
00:24:43.668 --> 00:24:45.288
within a 20-unit radius.

414
00:24:46.668 --> 00:24:50.528
Here in the middle, these maps show the spatial distribution of these

415
00:24:50.568 --> 00:24:53.928
niches in black across each patient's needle biopsy.

416
00:24:55.048 --> 00:24:58.608
On the left, we then quantify niche abundance across response

417
00:24:58.708 --> 00:24:59.068
groups.

418
00:24:59.948 --> 00:25:03.728
And overall, patients who achieved PCR after DTP

419
00:25:03.768 --> 00:25:07.688
had higher percentages of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes and more

420
00:25:07.788 --> 00:25:10.148
of these niches based on niche fraction.

421
00:25:11.388 --> 00:25:15.128
And finally, on the right, CellChat analysis suggests that T

422
00:25:15.228 --> 00:25:18.888
follicular helper cells are supporting B-cell activation and

423
00:25:18.928 --> 00:25:22.658
maturation through pathways including IL2, CD40,

424
00:25:23.028 --> 00:25:23.628
and ICAM.

425
00:25:24.888 --> 00:25:28.788
So in summary, TLS immune organization defines response

426
00:25:28.828 --> 00:25:31.708
to DTP in HER2-enriched early breast cancer.

427
00:25:32.428 --> 00:25:36.308
We find that distinct immune cell subsets, including T follicular

428
00:25:36.368 --> 00:25:40.118
helper-like CD4 positive T cells, LAMB3 positive

429
00:25:40.488 --> 00:25:44.228
mature dendritic cells, and B-cell populations associate with

430
00:25:44.268 --> 00:25:47.268
response to nivolumab, trastuzumab, and pertuzumab.

431
00:25:48.288 --> 00:25:51.908
We also find these populations to form a coordinated immune module that

432
00:25:51.988 --> 00:25:53.768
correlates with pathologic response.

433
00:25:54.828 --> 00:25:58.708
Spatial profiling further shows these cells to organize into TLSs

434
00:25:58.768 --> 00:26:02.408
across maturation states. And finally, TLS-associated

435
00:26:02.488 --> 00:26:06.388
niches are enriched in tumors from patients who achieve PCR and may help

436
00:26:06.488 --> 00:26:09.668
identify candidates for chemotherapy-free strategies.

437
00:26:11.088 --> 00:26:14.488
And with that, I'd like to thank the patients and their families for participating

438
00:26:14.508 --> 00:26:17.548
in the study, along with our clinical and research team,

439
00:26:17.768 --> 00:26:20.848
collaborators, and funding sources for their support.

440
00:26:20.858 --> 00:26:23.008
Thank you very much, and I'm happy to take questions.

441
00:26:29.708 --> 00:26:33.658
Thank you for a wonderful talk. Jan Kidrowski from University of Illinois at

442
00:26:33.668 --> 00:26:37.348
Cancer Center. Did you find any evidence of formation of high

443
00:26:37.388 --> 00:26:38.568
endothelial venules?

444
00:26:39.368 --> 00:26:43.228
Oh, yes. Excellent question. So as you can see here, we

445
00:26:43.308 --> 00:26:45.948
have, as I mentioned, the supporting structures.

446
00:26:47.488 --> 00:26:51.388
In our stroma population, you can sub-cluster

447
00:26:51.448 --> 00:26:55.368
endothelial cells into arterial, venule, HEV-like, and also

448
00:26:55.388 --> 00:26:57.198
lymphatic. So for this,

449
00:26:58.128 --> 00:27:01.988
I grouped together the lymphatic and the high endothelial venule cells,

450
00:27:02.388 --> 00:27:04.428
and they're in green. So yeah, they do exist.

451
00:27:04.457 --> 00:27:08.148
So treatment induced these populations to higher levels

452
00:27:08.268 --> 00:27:10.048
or to different states?

453
00:27:10.808 --> 00:27:14.648
That is a great question that we have not yet investigated

454
00:27:14.658 --> 00:27:17.578
because all of our samples were based on pre-treatment.

455
00:27:18.008 --> 00:27:21.988
So our goal was to figure out which of the immune responses or

456
00:27:22.048 --> 00:27:25.528
structures could predict for a response. So all of these are treatment naive.

457
00:27:25.888 --> 00:27:26.508
Oh, I see. Okay.

458
00:27:26.538 --> 00:27:27.948
Yes. But we do have post.

459
00:27:28.768 --> 00:27:31.768
That requires a lot more time and data analysis.

460
00:27:31.988 --> 00:27:32.128
Yeah.

461
00:27:32.237 --> 00:27:34.908
Yeah. But very fascinating to look at.

462
00:27:34.928 --> 00:27:37.888
That would be good to separate out the lymphatic and the venule populations-

463
00:27:37.948 --> 00:27:38.218
Yes

464
00:27:38.228 --> 00:27:40.268
... because they're doing different things. Thank you.

465
00:27:40.548 --> 00:27:42.008
Thank you.

466
00:27:43.488 --> 00:27:46.088
Aakash Patnaik from University of Chicago. Great talk.

467
00:27:46.668 --> 00:27:49.248
I was wondering about when you stratify your

468
00:27:50.308 --> 00:27:53.988
RCB0s to, let's say, the tumors with residual

469
00:27:54.068 --> 00:27:55.848
cancer burden. Do you see

470
00:27:56.788 --> 00:28:00.608
within the TLSs a difference in, let's say, proximity

471
00:28:00.728 --> 00:28:04.608
to macrophages or myeloid cells? Or have you done spatial

472
00:28:04.668 --> 00:28:07.188
analyses to understand the basis for

473
00:28:08.188 --> 00:28:10.728
the response versus lack of response?

474
00:28:10.848 --> 00:28:11.017
Mm-hmm.

475
00:28:11.488 --> 00:28:11.788
Yeah.

476
00:28:13.868 --> 00:28:15.838
Oh, sorry. I think I missed the question.

477
00:28:16.278 --> 00:28:16.498
So the question is-

478
00:28:16.508 --> 00:28:17.918
Did we see other cell types?

479
00:28:17.918 --> 00:28:21.618
Yeah. In the non-responders or the incomplete responders, did you see

480
00:28:22.707 --> 00:28:23.017
other

481
00:28:23.908 --> 00:28:27.868
close proximity to macrophages, myeloid cells, and other cell types that may drive

482
00:28:27.928 --> 00:28:28.468
resistance?

483
00:28:29.828 --> 00:28:32.128
Yes. Actually, that is a fascinating question.

484
00:28:33.468 --> 00:28:36.028
So when we did this initial analysis...

485
00:28:37.928 --> 00:28:41.868
Okay, so based on all of these cell types, we had a lot of significant

486
00:28:43.668 --> 00:28:46.628
cell types that were correlated with response.

487
00:28:46.668 --> 00:28:50.278
And so we grouped together these specific ones,

488
00:28:51.028 --> 00:28:54.288
including the PD-1 positive T follicular helper cells.

489
00:28:54.638 --> 00:28:58.408
Some other interesting ones that correlated with response were, for example,

490
00:28:58.428 --> 00:29:02.338
PD-1 positive exhausted T cells. And then anti-correlated

491
00:29:02.408 --> 00:29:06.198
with response/maybe predictive of resistance were

492
00:29:06.248 --> 00:29:09.908
SPP1 macrophages. And then now that's a

493
00:29:09.968 --> 00:29:11.298
separate story that

494
00:29:12.968 --> 00:29:13.388
I

495
00:29:15.028 --> 00:29:18.648
don't know if they're going to intertwine or not right now.

496
00:29:18.968 --> 00:29:22.858
But when I went to a lot of talks at ACR, there's a

497
00:29:22.888 --> 00:29:24.928
lot of myeloid-mediated suppression.

498
00:29:25.258 --> 00:29:28.228
And so some interesting ones would be the SPP1 macrophages.

499
00:29:28.268 --> 00:29:31.398
We also have the TREM2 and the full R2-positive

