554
00:32:41.888 --> 00:32:45.138
Okay, our next speaker is going to be Hongchang Fu from the Francis Crick Institute

555
00:32:45.138 --> 00:32:48.748
in London, and he's going to tell us about how nonsense-mediated decay

556
00:32:48.808 --> 00:32:50.708
inhibition can enhance antitumor immunity.

557
00:32:51.528 --> 00:32:54.798
Thank you, Dr. Margusev, for introducing. So my name is Hongchang.

558
00:32:54.937 --> 00:32:58.928
I was a former PhD student at University College London, and now I'm

559
00:32:58.988 --> 00:33:00.768
a postdoc at the Francis Crick Institute.

560
00:33:01.388 --> 00:33:05.028
And today I'm very glad I can have the opportunity to present our latest

561
00:33:05.068 --> 00:33:08.958
work on inhibiting nonsense-mediated decay to induce in

562
00:33:09.008 --> 00:33:12.788
vitro and in vivo and ex vivo tumor immunity, or antitumor

563
00:33:12.808 --> 00:33:16.648
immunity. This is my disclosure. None of these are to do with the

564
00:33:16.728 --> 00:33:18.068
study I am presenting today.

565
00:33:19.428 --> 00:33:22.907
So immunotherapy has really transformed treatment outcome and treatment

566
00:33:23.008 --> 00:33:25.588
regimens for many patients with cancer.

567
00:33:26.128 --> 00:33:29.168
However, vast majority of patients do not respond.

568
00:33:30.208 --> 00:33:33.848
And what we know about a response is that one of the best predictors to the

569
00:33:33.948 --> 00:33:37.568
immunotherapy response is the number of mutations that a tumor has.

570
00:33:38.168 --> 00:33:41.808
However, only less than 10% of tumor really features a high tumor

571
00:33:41.848 --> 00:33:45.528
mutation burden. And our question really remains, how do we

572
00:33:45.828 --> 00:33:49.588
benefit the remaining 90% plus of the tumor with low tumor

573
00:33:49.648 --> 00:33:50.428
mutation burden?

574
00:33:51.728 --> 00:33:55.488
And on top of that, what we know about a mutation is that not all mutations are

575
00:33:55.508 --> 00:33:59.468
really equal. And our previous study has shown that some classes

576
00:33:59.528 --> 00:34:03.028
of mutations are correlating better with immunotherapy response,

577
00:34:03.548 --> 00:34:07.088
and this is frame shift mutations, FS indels, which has the

578
00:34:07.128 --> 00:34:11.008
potential to translate to highly non-self and immunogenic peptides.

579
00:34:12.109 --> 00:34:16.008
However, it always introduce the formation of premature

580
00:34:16.048 --> 00:34:19.649
termination codeon, which then leads to the degradation by the NMD

581
00:34:19.708 --> 00:34:22.808
pathway and leading to no antigen formation.

582
00:34:23.928 --> 00:34:27.788
So what is an NMD pathway? In a setting where the PTC

583
00:34:27.798 --> 00:34:31.728
is formed in the middle of the transcripts, the ribosome will stop translating

584
00:34:32.089 --> 00:34:35.908
at a PTC, and this will lead to the activation of the NMD

585
00:34:35.968 --> 00:34:38.968
pathway, resulting in the decay of the mRNA.

586
00:34:40.908 --> 00:34:42.978
And for the time being, I will not go into the details.

587
00:34:43.348 --> 00:34:46.069
We know that the NMD is efficient, but it's not perfect.

588
00:34:46.528 --> 00:34:49.408
Some transcripts do escape the NMD

589
00:34:49.508 --> 00:34:53.339
pathway. Our prior study has demonstrated that

590
00:34:53.368 --> 00:34:57.348
the NMD escaped FS transcripts do correlate with the better

591
00:34:57.368 --> 00:35:00.808
clinical benefits because those are the ones being presented to the

592
00:35:01.668 --> 00:35:03.438
immune system and being recognized.

593
00:35:04.448 --> 00:35:08.258
Inevitably, they will be under negative selection because they are being recognized

594
00:35:08.268 --> 00:35:11.328
by the immune system, and there wouldn't be any selections for the

595
00:35:11.408 --> 00:35:14.588
NMD-inducing transcripts because they are never expressed.

596
00:35:15.268 --> 00:35:18.048
And that suggests there will be an untapped pool of

597
00:35:19.248 --> 00:35:20.868
highly immunogenic neoantigens.

598
00:35:22.108 --> 00:35:25.808
And given those, we hypothesize at a DNA level, we're able to find,

599
00:35:26.268 --> 00:35:30.208
FS mutations. And then at RNA level, there are associated PTC

600
00:35:30.248 --> 00:35:34.008
transcripts, and then we express them into FS proteins,

601
00:35:34.348 --> 00:35:37.728
load it onto the MHC class 1 complex on the tumor cells,

602
00:35:38.148 --> 00:35:41.668
being recognized by the T cells, get activated, and leading to

603
00:35:41.708 --> 00:35:43.128
successful tumor cell killing.

604
00:35:44.388 --> 00:35:48.158
So in order to do this, we have firstly to identify a successful

605
00:35:48.268 --> 00:35:50.508
inhibition target to inhibit the NMD.

606
00:35:51.248 --> 00:35:55.208
To do this, we correlate nine biological and clinical parameters to rank

607
00:35:55.288 --> 00:35:59.108
all the NMD-associated genes. And

608
00:35:59.208 --> 00:36:01.698
SMG1 appears to be the top-scoring candidate.

609
00:36:02.488 --> 00:36:06.248
And SMG1 is a kinase that phosphorylates the NMD

610
00:36:06.288 --> 00:36:10.088
complex, and which features promising inhibition

611
00:36:10.108 --> 00:36:14.048
targets for this study.Next, to see if such an

612
00:36:14.088 --> 00:36:17.908
inhibition strategy have a clinical impact, we have employed a

613
00:36:18.308 --> 00:36:22.268
preclinical model called a patient-derived tumor fragment model.

614
00:36:22.328 --> 00:36:26.268
This is a novel class of preclinical model that preserves the

615
00:36:26.308 --> 00:36:29.888
tumor ecosystem as well as the tissue architecture.

616
00:36:30.528 --> 00:36:34.068
There has been study that demonstrates the ex vivo response from the

617
00:36:34.088 --> 00:36:38.018
patient-derived tumor fragments correlates with the clinical response from

618
00:36:38.028 --> 00:36:41.048
patients receiving anti-PD-1 therapy.

619
00:36:41.088 --> 00:36:45.068
In our cohort, we have formed a N equals to 15 samples

620
00:36:45.188 --> 00:36:47.428
derived from patients with colorectal cancer.

621
00:36:48.148 --> 00:36:52.108
And most of those features a proficient MMR status, which means

622
00:36:52.168 --> 00:36:52.848
that they feature

623
00:36:53.648 --> 00:36:56.088
low immunogenicity and low T cell activation.

624
00:36:57.208 --> 00:37:00.468
So the way we do this is to inhibit the SMG1

625
00:37:00.508 --> 00:37:04.328
in ex vivo with SMG1 inhibitors.

626
00:37:04.408 --> 00:37:08.258
After 96 hours, we assess the activation by high dimensional

627
00:37:08.328 --> 00:37:09.078
flow cytometry.

628
00:37:10.068 --> 00:37:13.778
And what we observe is a significant increase of a T cell activation,

629
00:37:14.348 --> 00:37:17.147
as represented by PD-1 positive CD8 T cells.

630
00:37:17.888 --> 00:37:21.828
However, such an activation was not observed on the normal adjacent

631
00:37:21.888 --> 00:37:25.788
tissue, which confirms the tumor specificity of such inhibition

632
00:37:25.868 --> 00:37:29.488
strategy. In parallel, we have also performed

633
00:37:29.528 --> 00:37:32.508
single-cell RNA sequencing and TCR sequencing.

634
00:37:32.548 --> 00:37:36.088
What we observe is a significant upregulation of cytotoxic

635
00:37:36.188 --> 00:37:38.798
molecules as well as T cell expansion.

636
00:37:40.348 --> 00:37:44.328
So we see this PD-1 positive CD8 T cells being increased.

637
00:37:44.858 --> 00:37:48.438
So we wanted to know if this actually sensitized the immunotherapy response.

638
00:37:49.148 --> 00:37:51.488
To do this, we have employed a very aggressive

639
00:37:52.308 --> 00:37:55.468
immune refractory tumor model called Lewis Lung Carcinoma.

640
00:37:56.488 --> 00:38:00.068
What we can observe is single agent SMG1 inhibition has

641
00:38:00.128 --> 00:38:04.088
achieved comparable tumor control

642
00:38:04.128 --> 00:38:07.708
to single agent anti-PD-1 therapy, and combo therapy has achieved

643
00:38:07.808 --> 00:38:10.228
superior tumor control than any other single agent

644
00:38:11.188 --> 00:38:11.728
therapies.

645
00:38:12.708 --> 00:38:15.548
What has been fueling this T cell activation and

646
00:38:16.568 --> 00:38:20.268
tumor control is the activation of CD8 T cells,

647
00:38:20.468 --> 00:38:24.108
as represented by PD-1 positive CD8 T cells, in line

648
00:38:24.568 --> 00:38:28.498
with ex vivo results. In addition to that, we can also see a

649
00:38:28.528 --> 00:38:32.148
significant increase of the T cell activation on CD4

650
00:38:32.188 --> 00:38:35.868
non-Treg population. This is co-expressed with

651
00:38:35.928 --> 00:38:39.548
a range of co-stimulatory molecules as well as T cell clonal

652
00:38:39.628 --> 00:38:40.188
expansion.

653
00:38:41.708 --> 00:38:45.528
So what we observe is a T cell activation, but we don't know what this T

654
00:38:45.618 --> 00:38:48.168
cell is seeing and the molecular basis behind that.

655
00:38:48.688 --> 00:38:50.528
To do this, we switched to cell lines.

656
00:38:51.288 --> 00:38:52.928
After inhibition, we can see a

657
00:38:54.168 --> 00:38:57.968
upregulation of a range of PTC containing transcripts and

658
00:38:58.088 --> 00:38:58.208
in

659
00:39:00.148 --> 00:39:03.888
silico translation has demonstrate the SMG1 inhibition leads to

660
00:39:03.948 --> 00:39:07.728
upregulation of neoantigens and induce a high TMV-like

661
00:39:07.768 --> 00:39:08.928
state in the cell lines.

662
00:39:10.388 --> 00:39:14.288
After performing the immunopeptidomics, we have identified a unique subset

663
00:39:14.548 --> 00:39:18.308
of peptides that they only upregulated upon the NMD inhibition.

664
00:39:19.368 --> 00:39:23.268
And all of those are predicted to be the NMD inducing ones, and which

665
00:39:23.328 --> 00:39:26.928
indicates that the SMG1 inhibition has stabilized these NMD

666
00:39:26.968 --> 00:39:28.908
inducing transcripts to be degraded.

667
00:39:30.058 --> 00:39:33.808
And here, I am showing you two neoantigens arised from

668
00:39:33.868 --> 00:39:34.988
a same transcript.

669
00:39:36.568 --> 00:39:40.348
So we have identified these neoantigens, but we don't know if they are immunogenic.

670
00:39:41.008 --> 00:39:44.888
To do this, we have performed in vitro priming by deriving the dendritic

671
00:39:44.968 --> 00:39:48.888
cells and mature them, pulse them with the identified peptides, and co-culture

672
00:39:48.948 --> 00:39:50.108
them with naive T cells.

673
00:39:51.048 --> 00:39:54.968
After two rounds of priming, we restimulate the CD8 T cells

674
00:39:55.008 --> 00:39:58.928
with the identified peptides. And as you can see here, four out of the

675
00:39:59.008 --> 00:40:02.948
six peptide we've identified has shown comparable immunogenicity as

676
00:40:03.008 --> 00:40:05.928
one of the standard model antigen, NY-ESO.

677
00:40:07.348 --> 00:40:11.228
So we know the antigens are immunogenic, but in this system, we

678
00:40:11.268 --> 00:40:13.548
don't know if they are NMD inhibition dependent.

679
00:40:14.308 --> 00:40:17.568
To do this, we have modified a previously reported reporter.

680
00:40:18.548 --> 00:40:21.048
One is degraded by the NMD pathway, and that

681
00:40:22.948 --> 00:40:26.768
induces higher NY-ESO expression only upon the NMD inhibition.

682
00:40:27.528 --> 00:40:30.927
And the other construct, called NMD negative, that

683
00:40:30.987 --> 00:40:34.648
escapes the NMD degradation, and that induce constitutive

684
00:40:34.908 --> 00:40:38.008
NY-ESO expression regardless of the NMD inhibition.

685
00:40:39.348 --> 00:40:43.118
After that, we transduced both constructs into the cell lines,

686
00:40:43.628 --> 00:40:47.608
and then co-culture with the T cells that recognize the NY-ESO antigen.

687
00:40:48.298 --> 00:40:51.438
And then assess the immunogenicity via flow cytometry.

688
00:40:52.708 --> 00:40:56.598
What we can see here is the NMD inhibition actually promotes the T cell activation,

689
00:40:57.068 --> 00:41:00.908
but it's only being observed in NMD positive, but not in the NMD

690
00:41:00.948 --> 00:41:04.868
negative, suggesting such an activation is in a NMD

691
00:41:04.908 --> 00:41:06.088
inhibition dependent manner.

692
00:41:06.908 --> 00:41:10.638
And not only that, we can also see such an activation is

693
00:41:10.688 --> 00:41:14.098
also antigen dependent, because when we block out MHC class one,

694
00:41:14.628 --> 00:41:14.848
such an

695
00:41:15.888 --> 00:41:16.938
activation is gone.

696
00:41:18.548 --> 00:41:21.988
And on top of that, we can also see that the SMG1

697
00:41:22.028 --> 00:41:25.728
inhibition promotes also the T cell mediated tumor cell killing, as

698
00:41:25.808 --> 00:41:29.088
evidenced by a significant reduction on the relative cell growth.

699
00:41:30.788 --> 00:41:34.688
And very last but not least, I hope I have convinced you with our story that

700
00:41:34.728 --> 00:41:38.468
we identified several FS mutants and then get these PTC

701
00:41:38.568 --> 00:41:42.218
containing transcripts expressed, and then translate them into

702
00:41:42.348 --> 00:41:45.848
FS-derived proteins, get them loaded onto the MHC class one

703
00:41:45.868 --> 00:41:49.368
complex on the tumor cells, being recognized by the T cells,

704
00:41:49.668 --> 00:41:53.468
eliciting a successful immune response, as evidenced by our

705
00:41:53.568 --> 00:41:57.428
MHC class one dependent T cell activation evidenced in in

706
00:41:57.448 --> 00:42:00.068
vitro, in vivo, and ex vivo model systems.

707
00:42:01.248 --> 00:42:04.468
And at very last, this is a huge collaborative work.

708
00:42:04.888 --> 00:42:08.408
I would like to thank everybody who's been involved in this work, especially the

709
00:42:08.448 --> 00:42:12.308
patients and their carers and all of our collaboration labs who's been involved in

710
00:42:12.348 --> 00:42:12.748
this work.

711
00:42:13.648 --> 00:42:16.408
Thank you very much for your attention, and I will be very happy to take any

712
00:42:16.448 --> 00:42:16.887
questions.

713
00:42:23.218 --> 00:42:25.638
That was a great talk, Hongjun. Maybe I can ask the first question.

714
00:42:26.158 --> 00:42:27.538
Oh, we have a question. Yeah.

715
00:42:28.278 --> 00:42:30.138
I was also going to say that was a great talk.

716
00:42:30.258 --> 00:42:34.108
So is the MND pathway pretty ubiquitous across all different

717
00:42:34.138 --> 00:42:36.658
cell types or inflammatory

718
00:42:36.698 --> 00:42:40.398
conditions? And does it ever target viral

719
00:42:40.558 --> 00:42:42.378
mRNAs that are being translated?

720
00:42:43.258 --> 00:42:43.998
So it's a

721
00:42:44.978 --> 00:42:48.258
pan-mammalian eukaryotic RNA

722
00:42:48.738 --> 00:42:52.378
surveillance pathway. So it's being presented in all tissues.

723
00:42:52.398 --> 00:42:56.338
But what we suspect is that tumor cells relies more on the NMD pathways than

724
00:42:56.378 --> 00:43:00.138
normal cells because they need to handle the higher mutational burden.

725
00:43:00.218 --> 00:43:04.098
So in an evolutionary perspective, the tumor cells will rely more on the NMD

