00:43:04.158 --> 00:43:04.498
pathway.

727
00:43:05.218 --> 00:43:06.498
For any particular reason?

728
00:43:07.358 --> 00:43:11.138
Well, from evolutionary trajectory, I guess, because when a tumor

729
00:43:11.178 --> 00:43:15.098
needs to evade the tumor immunosurveillance, they need to down-regulate all

730
00:43:15.138 --> 00:43:18.498
these neoantigens in order to escape the

731
00:43:18.538 --> 00:43:19.498
immunosurveillance.

732
00:43:19.778 --> 00:43:23.218
Okay. And so if there's an infection, would it be upregulated, for

733
00:43:23.278 --> 00:43:25.938
instance, out of the tumor setting?

734
00:43:26.898 --> 00:43:30.528
Well, I don't think I can give you an answer to this question, but

735
00:43:30.738 --> 00:43:32.318
we do encounter this problem when

736
00:43:33.178 --> 00:43:37.058
identifying the clonal expansion because when we do this...

737
00:43:38.178 --> 00:43:38.358
Sorry.

738
00:43:40.218 --> 00:43:44.098
So when you see the clonal expansion in our ex vivo results, we actually filter out

739
00:43:44.158 --> 00:43:48.018
the viral reactive clones in order to get us a clear signal.

740
00:43:49.458 --> 00:43:50.338
Okay, thank you.

741
